The NSA affair highlights the complete absence of debate on intelligence
How to explain the contradictory attitude of the French government, which on the one hand takes offense in public by summoning the ambassador of the United States on October 21, and on the other prohibits the overflight of the territory by the Bolivian presidential plane, on the basis of the rumor of the presence on board of Edward Snowden?
In my opinion, there are two levels of response from the French government.
When François Hollande telephones Barack Obama or when Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius summons the United States Ambassador, they react to a real discovery, which is that of the extent of American surveillance of all communications in France.
Isn&#39;t it surprising to read in the columns of Le Monde a few weeks apart on the one hand the reproduction of American diplomatic correspondence and on the other hand a condemnation of the tapping of the Quai d&#39;Orsay by the NSA?
Wouldn&#39;t there be a vague hypocrisy on your part?
The journalistic approach is not a moral positioning, but the search for the interest and relevance of information that allows each citizen to form an opinion.
When WikiLeaks lifts the veil on the analysis by American diplomacy of political or other issues throughout the world, we consider that, with regard to American power, this constitutes an important light.
When we describe American interception systems against French diplomacy in the United States, it is in no way to be indignant at this practice, it is to describe the world as it is.
Did France benefit from information provided by the NSA concerning terrorist operations targeting our interests?
Can we deprive ourselves of American collaboration?
The establishment for roughly ten years of very powerful technological interception tools by the United States, but also by France, has officially been justified by the fight against terrorism.
Moreover, in this field, France and the United States in particular have set up procedures for cooperation and exchanges of information on an almost daily basis, which are described by both sides as essential.
For example, the presence of Mohammed Merah in the tribal areas in Miranshah was reported to the French thanks to the means of the NSA.
France may be led, for example, to transmit entire blocks of data on the Sahel region to American services, and, in return - as we have already quickly said - the Americans can give information to the French on other regions of the world.
So the basic question behind this NSA affair is not so much the ability or the right of countries to equip themselves with interception tools, as the question of the total absence of prior debate, particularly within Parliaments, on the justification for such systems, the scope that should be theirs, and, ultimately, the question of violations of freedoms.
What is the United States really risking? a degradation of their image?
We may denounce them, but I don&#39;t see how they can be punished.
The risk run by the Americans may be twofold.
The first is when their allies - and this has been the case recently - learn that their leaders, sometimes at the highest level of their state, have been monitored.
This is the case of Brazil and Germany, two countries where diplomatic relations with the United States have been strained.
Another effect may be more economical: more and more European or South American companies are reluctant, in the light of the revelations, to entrust their confidential data to American service providers subject to American laws, and therefore to the influence of the NSA.
Last element: the vast movement of revelations initiated by the media around the world, which is helping to trigger a debate on the surveillance practices of intelligence services that has hitherto been almost non-existent, could push legislators, including Americans, to reconsider the powers that they gave to their intelligence services.
