The new nicotine vaccine could suppress the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could suppress the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice against nicotine addiction for life.
More testing is needed before human trials begin, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said early signs were encouraging.
“We really hope that this kind of vaccine strategy can help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit, exhausting all the methods available on the market today, but find that their addiction is strong enough to overcome these different approaches,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to carry the genetic information needed to make anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies track down all the nicotine molecules present in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, which prevents the smoker from getting his nicotine fix.
During the tests, the vaccinated mice who were then given nicotine continued their activity normally.
But the mice that hadn&#39;t been vaccinated &quot;felt quiet,&quot; the researchers said, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines were found to be ineffective because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be repeated so frequently to keep antibody levels high that they were too expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future vaccine for human use was completely safe, it could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing any addiction to nicotine.
But it is more likely to be used by smokers who want to quit.
&quot;They will know that if they start smoking again, they won&#39;t enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it may help them break their bad habit,&quot; he added.
