FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on planes (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices door-to-door to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music – but not talk on their cellphones – under much-anticipated new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers shouldn&#39;t expect any immediate changes.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their planes meet the new guidelines and that they have updated crew member training manuals and aircraft stowage rules to comply.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their planes.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
&quot;Depending on the plan, we may approve expanded use of electronic devices very soon,&quot; the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They&#39;re not supposed to turn them back on until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their devices when getting off the plane before landing and not turn them back on until the plane has touched down.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are properly shielded from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their devices during takeoffs, landings and taxis, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with the changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will be working closely with carriers on this – it will benefit everyone,” Glading explained in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like “room attendants” when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be prohibited to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and text messages or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will need to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game actor Alec Baldwin was playing on his smartphone in 2011 when he was loudly kicked off an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the device was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will still need to be put away because they could hurt someone if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be prohibited.
Regulatory authority regarding cell phones rests with the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA May Lift Ban on Certain Electronic Devices During Takeoff and Landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said cellphones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are a real problem, not only because they could potentially interfere with navigation instruments, but because we know from the FCC that they could interfere with cell phone towers. if used on board,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee created by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow broader use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure on the FAA has grown in recent years to loosen restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce as device use has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least a third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began limiting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communications instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the day.
The new airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to resist electronic interference and FAA approved.
Airlines have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today&#39;s electronic devices generally emit much lower power radio transmissions than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices are downloading or sending data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for an easing of restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, company executives loaded an airliner with Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This inspired members of the FAA&#39;s advisory committee with mixed feelings about whether or not using the devices poses a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed interference from devices was real, although the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that the devices can interfere with an aircraft&#39;s systems, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to ask passengers to turn off their devices during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them common-sense arrangements for tech-equipped travellers.
&quot;We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety,&quot; said Roger Dow, president and director of the US Travel Association.
Rules regarding the use of electronic devices on board remain in force in Australia for the time being.
Australian air passengers will have to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during takeoff and landing despite a move by the United States to ease regulations on electronic devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration has left the door open for US carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their aircraft during critical phases of flight provided that they are in &quot;airplane&quot; mode.
Passengers can already do this for most of the flight, but many people find it a pain not to be able to access their eBooks during takeoff and landing.
Australian carriers are reviewing the ruling that requires US carriers to do significant work to meet the requirements, but said they have no immediate plans to change their procedures.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also said it was reviewing the announcement but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical phases of flight were still in place in Australia.
“CASA does not have specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices on airplanes,” she said.
The issue is subject to regulations which require aircraft operators to ensure that safety is maintained at all times and passengers to comply with the safety instructions given by crew members.
Virgin, which has already spoken to CASA about plans to expand use of its in-flight entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology, was open to a change but said it would follow the regulator.
“We would welcome a CASA review that would allow the use of electronic devices as we really believe it would improve the customer experience now that we have (the in-flight entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology) on our aircraft” , said a spokesperson.
Qantas said it was abiding by the current rules for the time being.
&quot;As per our current policy, electronic devices cannot be used during takeoff and landing, and we have no immediate plans to change this,&quot; she said.
The FAA decision applies to US airlines.
However, we are still interested in regulatory developments that could benefit passengers, and we will closely examine the FAA&#39;s decision and the reasons for it.
For US carriers, the impact of the decision will vary from airline to airline and depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will need to demonstrate that their planes can tolerate radio interference from electronic devices, as well as review manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage programs and instructions provided to passengers.
“Once an airline has verified its fleet tolerance, it may allow passengers to use lightweight portable electronic devices, such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at all altitudes,” the FAA said. .
In the rare event of low visibility, the crew will ask passengers to turn off their devices during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier devices be stowed safely under seats or in overhead bins during takeoff and landing.
