For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate between periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and visit hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but he contracted an infection which spread to his brain, creating a hematoma which he would carry with him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, getting him whatever treatment he could get.
“It&#39;s not easy,” adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., rush to the hospital to be the first, and you&#39;re not the first.
There are many patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since the death of Dr Bwelle&#39;s father in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor for every 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor for every 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of the country&#39;s health expenditure is carried out in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” explained Dr Bwelle.
And due to poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After watching his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to turn things around.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed more than 700 surgeries free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with around 30 people, they pile into vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to reach the villages that need the most help.
Luck does not always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed as heroes: the community throws a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free healthcare is cause for celebration, and Dr Bwelle – with his big smile and boundless energy – is more than happy to join in the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins seeing hundreds of patients.
&quot;We get 500 people on each visit,&quot; Bwelle said.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this mobile hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a collected pair of glasses or a free birth certificate – a document needed to attend school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
The operations are generally carried out in a school, a town hall or a house; after the procedure, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery room to make way for the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It&#39;s a grueling pace, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
&quot;They bang on drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working,&quot; Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they have accomplished.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgeries for free over the past year, and they know their presence can make all the difference to those they help.
A man explained that the free operation he underwent for a hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to supporting this mobile hospital and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical practices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don&#39;t know when he&#39;s sleeping,” said Katie O&#39;Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer with Dr. Bwelle&#39;s group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association to be able to carry out these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O&#39;Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle on his assignments, it&#39;s a hands-on learning opportunity they don&#39;t need. do not have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help mop up the blood or pass the instruments to Dr Bwelle,” said Miss O&#39;Malley.
It&#39;s not something you get to do in America when you&#39;re a sophomore medical student.
Student volunteers generally pay for their journey to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their board, transport and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
&quot;He&#39;s a hero, there&#39;s no doubt about it,&quot; said Katie O&#39;Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not about to die out.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others live happily ever after by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
&quot;I&#39;m so happy when I do this job,&quot; Mr. Bwelle added.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I&#39;m doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons why I do this.
