The two books published by Nora almost two years ago have already established that the one who was considered not to write had written a lot and well.
This book should definitely do it justice.
Yet we find there, once again, the temptation of ubiquity, intellectual vagrancy, the jubilation of jumping as if with both feet from one subject to another.
But we quickly understand that the disparate objects gathered in this book with such a beautiful title bring the second-hand dealer to one and the same passion: that of discovering the core of French identity.
Why these dramatic calls for national unity?
Identity: it is a preoccupation of the times.
Recently, we were collectively invited to give a definition.
But in the peremptory spirit of our leaders at the time, French identity was a timeless essence.
It was only necessary to deploy the accidents, and the affair, Jacobinism obliges, was entrusted to the prefects and the sub-prefects, authorized interpreters.
The one that Pierre Nora is tracking is quite different.
He does not pose as heir to an eternal Frenchness, he refuses definition.
An analyst worried about a familiar strangeness, he wanders in a forest of symbols, stopped at every step by an object in the form of a rebus, tormented by irritating questions.
Including this one, which is born of the company itself: why, in a country so permanently established within its borders, so anciently structured and solidly built, do we hear these dramatic calls for unity?
They are only so pressing, suggests Pierre Nora, to ward off the trouble born of the discords of French history.
Franks and Gauls, Armagnacs and Burgundians, Catholics and Protestants: the forces of division here are very old.
And the most emblematic is obviously the one that splits national history in two.
From the earthquake of the Revolution, the French have two histories and they have two nations, one monarchical, the other revolutionary.
The second wanted the death of the first, but without succeeding in denying it; anxious, on the contrary, to rediscover its sacredness and all the more eager for unity and indivisibility in that it had cut off the head of the one who was its obvious and powerful incarnation.
And, from there, an invincibly binary nation, divided between left and right, secularism and Catholicism, adoration and hatred of the revolution.
To make this singularity of French identity felt, nothing beats four steps outside France, so much so that Pierre Nora&#39;s American escapade could well be the heart of his book.
Because America and France have both made a revolution, drafted a declaration of rights, wanted to found a new society.
But the American cousinhood only better underlines what is unique to us.
There, men who had left their Old Regime in England and no longer had to worry about it.
Here, encumbered men of an indigenous Old Regime, and all the more radical.
There a consensual revolution when here it has sown drama and confit.
There founding fathers always honored, and here revolutionary ancestors whom it is difficult to make models, and who moreover killed each other.
There an institutional constancy, and here a cascade of constitutions, like so many mistakes to make up for and attempts to repeat.
The France that is leaving, the France that is coming
There was, however, a time when the French believed they could mend the torn dress of their history, and overcome the curse of the number two.
At this Third Republic, a central and creative moment, Pierre Nora showed great interest and even tenderness: saluting those who then worked to repair the revolutionary fracture, teaching schoolchildren everything that in old France obscurely prepared modern France and offering them a unified version of their history.
But this pacified identity only had a time.
Here it is again in debate, jostled by a new type of immigration, threatened by the rise of protesting minorities, absorbed in the European space.
The book therefore offers both a fascinating portrait of the France that is leaving and a circumspect sketch of the France that is coming.
With, as a bonus, the portrait of the historian, who should reserve some surprises.
We discover that the tramp was a homebody.
The man of multiple curiosities revolved, slightly obsessively, around the same idea.
The Edge Prowler stood in the center of the center.
And the one who, more than half a century ago, had submitted a subject on the idea of nation, but had withdrawn from the initiatory exercise of the thesis, confides to us, cum grano salis, that he will have finished by doing it.
Certainly in a less stiff, more fragmented and more subtle form.
But make no mistake, just as binding.
Because much more than the imposed figure of the university curriculum, this thesis speaks of the inner necessity of a life.
