But DNA analysis is still very time-consuming and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Identification has so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the State has on all citizens already on file.
This helps ensure that a person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or shop.
“We collect images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, in charge, at NEC France, of business development for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a picture of someone queuing in a store, follow their progress using facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
Added to this, more recently, is presence control.
&quot;A biometric time clock avoids the phenomenon of the buddy who points for another&quot;, justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those carried out from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain ATMs by inserting your card and placing your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces typing the secret code.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d&#39;Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and large retail chains: when paying in stores with their bank card, the customer does not enter their code , but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
&quot;If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the checkout thirty seconds less, it&#39;s appreciable&quot;, explains the director of a supermarket.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
&quot;Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people&#39;s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it&quot;, enumerates Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, for lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these discourses really convince users.
Privacy experts continue to worry.
&quot;Advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the enormous amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance&quot;, predicts Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Commissioner for Protection of privacy in Canada.
