Scientists have just shed light on how a dog&#39;s tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies have found that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog&#39;s perspective), while nervous dogs wag their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist from the University of Trento, said: &quot;Everyone knows that in humans the left side and the right side of the brain are involved in different ways in the stimuli that arouse emotions. positive or negative. »
Here we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that similarly to humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disorderly tail movements from other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies that featured other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It surely won&#39;t be long before we figure out why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: &quot;We showed dogs movies that had other dogs in them - either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factors - and we were able to manipulate the tail movement and show it like going more left or right. »
When the animals saw an expressionless dog wagging its tail to the right (from the perspective of the dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail swerving mostly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate spiked and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks dogs know from experience which movements they should and shouldn&#39;t be concerned about.
He added: &quot;If you repeatedly encounter other dogs and notice that most of the time their tail wagging to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side results in a less friendly, you will react according to this experience. »
The researchers say the results could help owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pets&#39; emotions.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol&#39;s School of Veterinary Science, clarified that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in dogs. canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs went more easily towards a robot dog when its tail was wagging to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – l opposite of what appears in the Italian study. »
He said the differences could be because the dogs in the different studies didn&#39;t fully view the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he said.
“While there is a lot of evidence from different mammals that indicates that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, there are still many details that need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said. .
However, given how easily their behaviors can be recorded, it surely won&#39;t be long before we understand why their tails sometimes move to one side and sometimes to the other.
