Obama&#39;s 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is a 2nd year medical student at Harvard Medical School.
I&#39;m reading an awfully sad book these days.
This is a book that I thought would cheer me up through the gloom of 2nd year med and give me hope.
It&#39;s called &quot;The Audacity to Win&quot; and it&#39;s the memoir of Barack Obama&#39;s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patients&#39; medical reports at night and go to bed, this book takes me back to the days when politics inspired millions and speeches could take your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide victory and news anchors took time to reflect on the historic nature of the moment.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents kept all the diaries they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing towards the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama&#39;s transition period before taking office in 2008, he had 82% favorable opinions.
And then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a difficult awakening, it&#39;s like coming out of a dream.
It is hard to remember those days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of the opportunities of the past.
The change really happened in the years since I first voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great accomplishments, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of our army from Iraq, to the end of the &quot;neither seen nor known&quot; and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Further, I believe partisan filibuster has destroyed too many efforts to move our nation forward on immigration reforms, public health care, and closing Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration to my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide explanations.
I am on the verge of political despair.
Republican stonewalling cannot explain the bugging of foreign leaders, nor the drone attacks on innocent foreign children.
She cannot explain that the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans, nor the indictment of whistleblowers who reveal government misdeeds.
It cannot justify the assassination of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without trial, nor the evasion of public funds and the overspending during presidential campaigns.
She can&#39;t substantiate the conclusions of a report that says the White House&#39;s efforts to silence the media are the &quot;most aggressive...since the Nixon administration.&quot;
And, more recently, she can&#39;t excuse the inability to design a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was signed into law.
I don&#39;t know if this is what I expected.
If, at 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that precede it.
Obviously, the electoral function is not predictable, because the opposition political party and the events that happen by chance, like the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all of the examples I&#39;ve listed above seem to be largely the administration&#39;s choice.
That&#39;s what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confused and unrefined alternative that did not seem to help determine his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected to a second term freed from the pressure of future elections, would deliver on the promises we had heard about for so long.
Yet, as the Positive Opinion Index dipped below 45% this week, it&#39;s even harder to look back to 2008 through this book.
He makes me long for the many promises that have flown away.
This week I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered huge losses to Clinton in the Pennsylvania Primaries.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team they needed to get back on track and stay true to their cause.
&quot;I want us to refocus on our talent,&quot; he said.
We must remember who we are.
Here we are 5 years later, Mr. President, and I no longer agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
