RBS suspends two forex traders
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its FX division according to two sources familiar with the matter, further showing that regulators&#39; global investigation into suspected FX market manipulation is starting to bear fruit.
Some of the world&#39;s biggest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed they are cooperating with regulators in investigations into the world&#39;s largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion US change hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the widening investigation which echoes the Libor interbank rate manipulation scandal.
The bank, which declined to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received requests for information from regulators.
&quot;The ongoing investigation into this matter is continuing and we are cooperating fully with the FCA and other regulators,&quot; a bank representative said two weeks ago.
Last month, sources familiar with the matter said RBS had passed records of emails and instant messages, sent to and by a former trader, to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and was reportedly suspended from his position as European head of spot trading for currencies at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European head of spot foreign exchange trading at Citi, was furloughed this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged.
Mr Usher&#39;s dossier included instant messages sent to and from bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, people familiar with the matter added.
UBS explained this week that it had taken legal action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating suspected foreign exchange market manipulation at a number of banks. Swiss.
Around the world, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the United States Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are looking into allegations made about bankers who colluded to manipulate rates on the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, people familiar with the matter said.
Banks have been sifting through instant messages and emails sent for years to find instances of wrongdoing.
News of the investigations has rattled traders in an industry that has been one of the biggest growth drivers for investment banking trading units in recent years, but has been challenged this year due to low currency volatility which limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to play it down by saying it&#39;s nearly impossible to manipulate the vast, highly liquid forex market, but senior traders say that&#39;s not necessarily true.
A senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily FX trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between exchange management platforms and the increasing use by banks of their own platforms internal &quot;explains that it is possible to start having an impact on the market at little cost&quot;.
The news came the same day Credit Suisse announced it had fired a trader working in its London Stock Exchange-traded funds office this week after he caused a $6 million loss late last year.
The bank promptly notified the relevant authorities and cooperated with regulators.
“We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the matter was brought under control,” said a representative of Credit Suisse.
