Precocious Puberty: Aging Earlier
Studies show that African American and Hispanic girls tend to hit puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical Changes Don&#39;t Mean Puberty Is Imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts think the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for precocious puberty
The tendency towards precocious puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter&#39;s breasts and pubic hair start growing at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, child endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
&quot;I spend a lot of time reassuring parents — usually that doesn&#39;t indicate a rapid move into full puberty,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as budding breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age at first menstrual period over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, while it was 12 three quarters in 1970.
&quot;Once the breasts have started to grow, it takes at least two or three years before menstruation begins,&quot; said Kaplowitz, also the author of &quot;Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This. Common Problem”.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will evolve.
There is some debate regarding what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered &quot;early&quot; when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before age 8.
In most cases, development slows or stops – something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may warrant testing by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems like tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones which can slow down growth and short stature in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone treatment are based on the child&#39;s age, rate of development, rate of growth, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is careful with medication but acknowledges that &quot;controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and young girls&#39; sense of being different from others.&quot;
The other big problem is understandable: Parents just don&#39;t want their very young daughters to menstruate.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they&#39;re going to handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about periods, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories made known to the public about the causes of precocious puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study conducted on girls aged 6 to 9 that linked body fat percentage to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanics of precocious puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger facial and pubic hair, the trend toward true precocious puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the subject.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
&quot;We have to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,&quot; said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk with their child.
“It may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls going through early puberty need to be reassured that, even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
