It made sense.
It didn&#39;t bother me.
How do you react today to the release of the four hostages from Niger?
I listen to what is being said.
The debate on ransoms in particular.
Some things annoy me, others less so.
I try to make a distinction between questions about my past as a hostage and my role as president of the &quot;Hostages of the World&quot; association, which allows me to put some distance, and seems much more interesting to me to land.
For example, I wonder about the definition of resilience.
Above all, I fight, with others, for the recognition of the legal status of the hostage.
I think there is a problem of semantics.
We must qualify the taking of hostages as &quot;political&quot; hostage taking - which is the case most of the time - and allow the hostages to have access to justice, to file a complaint and to bring their takers hostages before the International Criminal Court.
Today, once again, everyone is in compassion, in emotion, and rejoices in the release of these hostages.
But who says that these hostages could perhaps also have access to justice?
A court in The Hague is made for that.
Why don&#39;t we say to the hostage takers &quot;you flouted the rules of war, like those of all the Geneva conventions, we will bring you to justice&quot;?
It seems to me, however, well-founded, legitimate, struck by common sense.
This message is heard, but not listened to, and that shocks me.
This is my main fight.
