Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe&#39;s instructions, anyway?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe has definitely come to a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties that oppose the EU or campaign for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, garnered nearly five million votes in the September federal election and ousted the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats ) of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket weighing on national economies through joining the single currency, has led many to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits – that was only true for Greece.
Rather, the European system has burdened its members with exchange rates favorable to German exporters – something German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make drastic cuts in salaries and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise related to productivity in Europe.
As a result of “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at consumer expense – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas than the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, revolt is brewing, particularly in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the battered French economy to scramble.
Result: Marine Le Pen&#39;s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, sending the ruling Socialists to third place.
