A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L&#39;Express to this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
This is good news, but it does not particularly surprise me.
If in the past, species were described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our scientific knowledge of the classification of species.
It is also not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, a family, or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two species very close morphologically have been distinguished thanks to genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific humpback dolphins and the Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyzes have identified four species.
Why is this a significant discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had already been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only at this location.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a species more widely distributed on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered depending on the number of individuals existing on Earth, ie the stock, and the possibility it has of recovering from neighboring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become lower, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This mixing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can ultimately lead to the creation of new species.
You should know that the marine environment is the least well known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariana Trench, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on the search for life on other planets than on marine research and it is high time that this changed.
