It&#39;s been five years since my father disappeared from the world of the living.
At first I denied his death, I was talking about him in present tense,
I was so afraid of forgetting him or rather I didn&#39;t know how I was going to continue to &quot;visit&quot; him.
There is no recipe, no instructions for passing the invisible wall and finding your loved ones.
Then signs appeared.
The first time was the very strong feeling of his presence on the passenger seat while I was driving.
Another time, a gentle awakening in the middle of the night to look at his watch which never leaves me, placed on the bedside table.
It is the image of my smiling father who accompanies me in my daily actions.
Our mother passed away after her grueling battle with cancer.
At least that&#39;s what I thought the day I found his body empty, tense on this hospital bed with crumpled sheets.
Likewise, his funeral was a chilling farewell focused around the dim candlelight that framed his coffin.
I thought she was gone.
Little by little, in small daytime or nighttime appearances, a little shy, a little erased, she quickly came back to my mind, evolving as she took her place back in the landscape of my thoughts, which believed itself to be in mourning. .
And then, she revealed herself while revealing to me my own facets that I had not yet perceived, masked by my relationship with her.
So I learned and understood that I had in no way lost the person of my mother but simply a woman that I didn&#39;t really know, a woman who embodied this person during her stay in life.
By dying, this woman had perfected her life and freed the person I loved, and now I found her, full and whole.
This detour in the path of my life remains the most unexpected and the most beautiful.
It is a privilege to know that loved ones never leave us.
I look like my father, &quot;inside and out&quot; it seems.
I&#39;ve always been told that.
I never believed him at the time.
I had a difficult relationship with him until he became old, sick.
There, I was no longer afraid of him and I was able to love him.
One day he died.
For a long time, it accompanied me: when I quit smoking, when I was scared, when I was in pain...
He spoke to me, constantly encouraged me, he inhabited my body.
I saw his hands looking at mine, I lent him my body.
But it was never indiscreet.
I was able to have a personal life.
He left me my privacy.
It lasted a long time and then one day he left.
Finally, it was comfortable and reassuring to be understood, encouraged, advised.
I don&#39;t remember who said that dead people are not forgotten but invisible.
My parents are no more but I constantly feel them close to me.
Every event, every moment of my life makes me feel their presence because I always refer to them: what would they have said? what would they have thought? what would they have done?
I dream of them constantly, maybe not every night but several times a week for sure.
I often dream of the last moments that I have to share with them before it&#39;s too late, only there is always something that prevents me from accomplishing this moment.
I often wake up anxious when this happens to me and I deeply feel their absence.
Sometimes, certain dreams carry me on the contrary and are part of my story and indeed, they continue to live and share my life.
The day before my ultrasound where I was to find out the sex of my baby, I dreamed that I woke up, I climbed out of bed, my father was waiting for me on the landing and he was smiling at me and happy that I was waiting a little boy.
