You could say that New York City is where stand-up comedy was born in America: almost 100 years ago, vaudeville actor Frank Fay, who held the role of master of ceremonies at the Palace Theater, on Broadway, started telling jokes directly in front of the audience, in a conversational tone.
Fay&#39;s innovation has continued over the years, until it was picked up more recently by the New York Comedy Festival.
Created and overseen by Caroline Hirsch, the founder of the Carolines stand-up club, the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary this year, with more than 60 shows presented in small clubs and large theaters.
&quot;Most of the headliners emerged at the Carolinas, and were very successful, until they became too famous to play in a club,&quot; Hirsch said.
