Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents her two new group choreographies at Danse Danse: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by Satie&#39;s famous Gymnopédies piano solos.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from inky black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, just as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple line, takes its shape.
And this form will be that of the whole piece: a row of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, dressed entirely in black, only their hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the playing area, rush when the next spelling appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game of Henri Michaux is done in relay of solos, in a group in unison (a mass that is solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of &quot;Morning Glory&quot;, where, in solo, Chouinard carried out a series of choreographic tasks written on labels, posed in line at the front of the stage.
It&#39;s the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance floor, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux&#39;s poem, monotonous and monotonous in the auction, and will continue dancing.
And the music to start again, and the sequence to resume.
This sonorous and energetic discharge, long if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - creating images has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those hair that ruffles or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux&#39;s work, has imposed herself, with her tics.
Result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux&#39;s inks, like forms of Gestalt, open up a broader and more game-filled imagination than dance, which is more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers choppy by a strobe light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches on magic.
The public liked it, the welcome was warm.
Les Gymnopédies, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers take turns to play the scores.
Their musical clumsiness, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, pass the couples, in amorous duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, the writing is less binary.
Jesters appear, also familiar to Chouinard, sporting red noses, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnivorous, fleeing or playful.
The gestures, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridiculousness of the bodies in coitus, of the beings who merge.
But the play really takes off after the salute.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes possible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers romp about, go down among the spectators, gossip, smoke, short-circuit each other, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a skilfully calculated disorder that remain sensual.
Joy and madness transpire, and it is Chouinard&#39;s art, there, to contaminate the public.
