Pope Francis will appoint his first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new Catholic Church cardinals for the first time on Feb. 22, the Vatican announced Thursday.
Cardinals are the most senior clergymen in the Catholic Church behind the pope, and those who elect him, so Francis will appoint his first group of men who will ultimately choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, once a cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of a pope – this amounts to a group of 120 “Cardinal Electors”.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said a meeting of all existing cardinals would be held ahead of the ceremony in which bishops will be elevated to the dignity of cardinal, known under the name of consistory.
“Pope Francis has decided to communicate his decision to convene the February consistory in advance in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that by February the number of cardinal voters will likely have dropped.
He said a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as needed to bring the number of cardinal electors up to 120 and as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wanted.
Next year&#39;s consistory will be important because it will be the first since the election of Pope Francis in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a kind of tendency to favor Europe and in particular Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore the balance,” he added.
40% of Roman Catholics live in South America, but a small number of cardinals represent them.
The cardinals will also be the first to be chosen since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with considering ways to reform the church.
Previously, the pope decided alone.
“Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,” Valero explained.
He added that it was &quot;quite possible&quot; that Francis would ask the cardinals for advice.
But we have never experienced such a situation – it is completely new.
Valero said popes typically elevate bishops representing large communities to the rank of cardinal, but Francis was “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he will appoint.”
