Gérard de Villiers, the author of &quot;SAS&quot;, is dead.
He will never have known the word retirement.
Phenomenon of French publishing, Gérard de Villiers, who died Thursday at the age of 83, had just published his 200th SAS, &quot;La Vengeance du Kremlin&quot;.
In February, the New York Times named him &quot;the author of spy novels who knew too much&quot;.
He had just spent ten days in Afghanistan, the scene of the 198th and 199th installments of the famous series of spy novels.
Physically diminished by a very serious heart attack in December 2010, he moved during this trip with a walker.
And before Afghanistan, he had also gone back to Libya, Russia, Lebanon and Mali.
With four SAS published per year, Gérard de Villiers, born on December 8, 1929 in Paris, claimed to be unaware of the exact number of books sold since 1965 and the publication of &quot;SAS in Istanbul&quot;, the first of the series, nearly a year ago. &#39;a half-century.
&quot;Probably between 120 and 150 million all countries combined,&quot; he said last March.
His Burmese cat on his knees, in the living room of his huge apartment in a building on Avenue Foch a stone&#39;s throw from the Arc de Triomphe, his mischievous eye under his white hair, he quoted some of the languages in which the adventures of SAS have been translated: Italian, German, Russian, Greek, Japanese or Korean.
&quot;Not to mention the pirate editions,&quot; he added, pointing to a pile of books on the coffee table between the bronzes or ivories brought back from the 130 countries surveyed to place his novels there.
For the price of a pack of cigarettes, the reader is entitled to the traditional cover with the photo of a young woman with advantageous breasts, carrying a pistol or an assault rifle.
Inside, His Serene Highness (SAS) Prince Malko Linge, penniless Austrian aristocrat and contract agent for the CIA to pay for repairs to the family castle, sets off on the heels of all the bad guys on earth, communists of the 70s and 80, then jihadists from the 90s.
Each book has the same recipe: a large dose of geopolitics and exoticism, a few hard sex scenes, a touch of violence and torture.
&quot;I never claimed to be a literary author&quot;, explained Gérard de Villiers.
I consider myself a storyteller who writes to entertain people I don&#39;t send a message to.
He worked &quot;like the great pre-war reporters, of the Albert London type, who went on the spot and came back with real and long investigations&quot;.
SAS&#39;s father said &quot;to make a kind of geopolitical soap opera&quot;.
&quot;I constantly follow my files (Afghanistan, Syria, etc.) before leaving,&quot; added Gérard de Villiers.
On the spot, I meet journalists, including those of the AFP, diplomats, people of the services that I know for some for twenty or thirty years.
As a result, many of his SAS are often prescient: thus, a month before the attack on a Syrian regime command center that killed several senior officials, he told the story in &quot;Le Chemin de Damas&quot;.
In &quot;Les Fous de Benghazi&quot;, he was the first to reveal the existence of a secret CIA command center in this city, the cradle of the Libyan revolt.
In 1980, he staged the assassination of Egyptian President Anouar El-Sadat in &quot;The Cairo Plot&quot;, a year before the attack.
In October 2012, in &quot;Panic in Bamako&quot;, he recounted the columns of 4X4 jihadists who descended on the Malian capital.
I am not a diviner, Gérard de Villiers defended himself, I simply make assumptions from countries that I know well and, from time to time, some of my assumptions come true.
After these trips to often troubled areas, he settled down for a month behind his IBM daisy typewriter dating from 1976 &quot;all the parts of which have been changed&quot;.
300 pages later, he wrote the word &quot;END&quot; and corrected each page in pen.
On the walls of his office hang AK-47 assault rifles, erotic photos and photos of the author with African warlords.
Regularly pinned for machismo by feminist leagues and for racism by human rights organizations, Gérard de Villiers dismissed these accusations in two sentences.
Some women are sex objects in my books, but others are beautiful, smart, and brave women.
I am always well received in Africa where I have many readers.
Gérard de Villiers had said it: &quot;Malko Linge, like all heroes, is ageless&quot;.
He will not die and will not retire.
Not more than me.
